# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# benchpkg is **AirspeedVelocity.jl's primary
# benchmarking CLI** ŌĆö runs benchmarks of a Julia
# package across multiple git revisions and reports
# the JSON results.  Pivots from R295 kiln-sprof
# (Common Lisp clingon) into the **Julia language
# tooling cluster** ŌĆö corpus's first documented Julia
# CLI.  Sister tools: `benchpkgtable` (renders the
# JSON results as a table), `benchpkgplot` (renders
# as a plot), all three installed by `julia -e
# 'using AirspeedVelocity; AirspeedVelocity.install()
# '` to `~/.julia/bin`.  **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's
# **first documented Julia CLI** ŌĆö adds Julia
# Comonicon.jl to the cross-language CLI taxonomy
# (35 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **Julia
# `Comonicon.jl` library** at src/BenchPkg.jl:5 ŌĆö the
# **modern Julia CLI framework** by Roger Luo
# (comonicon/Comonicon.jl).  Comonicon is the
# de-facto standard for building Julia CLI tools;
# alternatives include ArgParse.jl (older, ArgParse
# Python port), DocOpt.jl (docopt port), and
# ArgMacros.jl.  Distinct from ArgParse.jl's
# `@add_arg_table! s begin ... end` (data-as-spec) ŌĆö
# Comonicon uses the JULIA FUNCTION SIGNATURE
# ITSELF as the CLI spec: positional arguments are
# function positionals, options are keyword
# arguments, defaults are `=` syntax, types are Julia
# type annotations.  Documents the **function-
# signature-as-CLI-spec pattern** ŌĆö distinct from
# R291 CL `command-line-arguments` plist spec, R292
# Erlang 5-tuple spec, R294 Pharo Smalltalk cascade
# spec, and R295 CL clingon `make-option` calls.
# Comonicon's signature-as-spec is similar to Python
# fire/typer but EXPLICIT about types via Julia's
# typed annotations.  Corpus's **first documented
# function-signature-as-CLI-spec library**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **docstring-
# as-help-source** at src/BenchPkg.jl:7-51 ŌĆö the
# Julia docstring ABOVE the `@main` function provides
# ALL CLI help text, AND its `# Arguments / # Options
# / # Flags` sections drive SHORT-NAME DISCOVERY.  For
# example, `-r, --rev <arg>` in the `# Options`
# section tells Comonicon that `rev` has short alias
# `-r`.  No separate annotation, no `@option(short
# = 'r')` attribute ŌĆö the DOCSTRING IS THE SPEC.
# Documents the **docstring-driven short-flag
# discovery pattern** ŌĆö distinct from R291 CL
# `#\h` character literal annotation, R292 Erlang
# `$h` character literal, R294 Pharo `(ClapFlag id:
# #version)` symbol identifier, and R295 clingon
# `:short-name #\A` keyword arg.  Comonicon's
# approach makes the CLI surface AUTO-DOCUMENT
# itself ŌĆö the help text and the spec are literally
# the same artifact.  Corpus's **first documented
# docstring-driven CLI spec**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **Julia
# semicolon-separated positional/kwarg split** at
# src/BenchPkg.jl:52-66 ŌĆö Julia syntax `function
# foo(a, b; c=1, d=2)` PUTS `a, b` as positionals
# and `c, d` as keyword arguments, separated by `;`.
# `benchpkg(package_name::String=""; rev::String=
# "...", ...)` declares ONE positional (with
# default "") and TWELVE keyword arguments.
# Comonicon maps positionals to CLI positionals and
# kwargs to CLI options.  Documents the **semicolon-
# delimited positional-kwarg split pattern** ŌĆö
# distinct from Python `def foo(a, b=None, *, c=None)`
# (where `*` separates positional-or-kwarg from
# kwarg-only) and from R295 CL `(&key tcp stdio ...)`
# (where `&key` separates required from keyword).
# Julia's semicolon syntax is structurally simpler:
# everything before `;` is positional, everything
# after is keyword.  Corpus's **first documented
# semicolon-delimited CLI spec**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **Julia
# Bool-typed kwarg ŌåÆ CLI flag** at src/BenchPkg.jl:59/
# 65 ŌĆö `tune::Bool=false` becomes `--tune` (CLI
# flag, no value), and `dont_print::Bool=false`
# becomes `--dont-print`.  Comonicon SPECIAL-CASES
# `Bool`-typed kwargs as boolean flags rather than
# `--tune=true`/`--tune=false` value pairs.
# Documents the **Bool-type ŌåÆ boolean-flag
# coercion pattern** ŌĆö distinct from R291 CL
# `(:type Boolean :optional t)` (typed but
# value-required) and R292 Erlang `boolean` ArgSpec
# (also value-required: `--enable-ssl true`).
# Comonicon adopts the convention that `Bool` means
# "presence-only flag", while value-required boolean
# would need `String` or explicit handling.  Corpus's
# **first documented Bool-as-flag-not-value CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **Julia
# snake_case ŌåÆ CLI kebab-case auto-conversion** at
# src/BenchPkg.jl:55/62/64/65 ŌĆö `output_dir::String=
# "."` becomes `--output-dir`, `bench_on::String=""`
# becomes `--bench-on`, `nsamples_load_time::Int=5`
# becomes `--nsamples-load-time`, `dont_print::Bool=
# false` becomes `--dont-print`.  Underscores in
# Julia kwarg names AUTO-TRANSLATE to dashes in CLI
# flag names ŌĆö a Comonicon convention.  Documents
# the **snake_case ŌåÆ kebab-case auto-conversion
# pattern** ŌĆö distinct from R295 CL clingon
# `:long-name "all-threads"` (explicit kebab-case
# string) and R291 CL `("help" #\h)` (explicit
# string).  Comonicon's convention reduces
# boilerplate: write idiomatic Julia kwarg names,
# get idiomatic CLI flag names.  Corpus's **first
# documented underscoreŌåÆdash auto-conversion CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **type-
# parameterized kwarg dispatch** at src/BenchPkg.jl:
# 64 ŌĆö `nsamples_load_time::Int=5` annotates the
# kwarg with Julia's `Int` type.  Comonicon uses
# this annotation to PARSE the CLI value: a string
# arriving from argv gets `parse(Int, ...)` applied
# before binding to the kwarg.  `String` kwargs
# bypass parsing.  Documents the **Julia-type-
# annotation-drives-parse pattern** ŌĆö distinct from
# R295 CL clingon `:integer` kind keyword (CLOS
# class), R292 Erlang `{integer, 300}` ArgSpec tuple,
# and R294 Pharo `(self positional: #port)
# asInteger` (explicit at-read coerce).  Comonicon's
# approach is the MOST IMPLICIT: the type annotation
# IS the parse instruction.  Corpus's **first
# documented type-annotation-drives-parse CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: benchpkg uses **`@main`
# macro for entry-point declaration** at src/
# BenchPkg.jl:52 ŌĆö `Comonicon.@main function
# benchpkg(...) ... end` is the Comonicon decorator
# that REGISTERS the function as the CLI entry
# point.  At compile time, the macro:
#   1. Parses the docstring for help text + short
#      flags
#   2. Walks the function signature for positionals/
#      kwargs/types/defaults
#   3. Generates a wrapper that parses argv against
#      the spec and calls `benchpkg(...)` with the
#      parsed values
#   4. Adds an `install` entry point so `julia -e
#      'using BenchPkg; BenchPkg.install()'` writes
#      a `~/.julia/bin/benchpkg` launcher script
# Documents the **compile-time macro entry-point
# registration pattern** ŌĆö distinct from R294 Pharo
# `<commandline>` pragma annotation, R291 CL
# `defparameter *command-line-spec*` runtime data,
# and R266 Python Click `@click.command()` runtime
# decorator.  Comonicon's `@main` is COMPILE-TIME ŌĆö
# the executable wrapper is GENERATED, not
# interpreted at startup.  Corpus's **first
# documented compile-time CLI macro**.
